For the items below, please name what you see. Write as many different names as possible (i.e., you could answer with both 'cup' and 'mug' in response to a coffee cup. 
Whenever possible, make sure you include at least one single-word name for the item(s) pictured. A multiple-word answer is acceptable, but only if it's a conventional *name* for the item(s) pictured. So 'coffee cup,' 'teacup,' or even 'drinking vessel' would be reasonable. However, please AVOID roundabout descriptions ('the thing you put coffee in') or specific details about the image ('white teacup').
If English is not your native language, how old were you when you learned it?

Thank you for your help with this project. We're testing out some stimuli to be used in an experiment, to get a sense of the range of responses. Thus the responses you give us will be used in design, but not in data analysis.

We're most interested in the choices made by native New Zealand English speakers. If you don't meet this criterion, feel free to complete the survey, but be sure to tell us what your background is.
Were there any objects you didn't understand, or you didn't know the English name for?
When you learned English, what country did you live in?
